A Libellula pulchella is a species of dragonfly that belongs to the family Libellulidae. It is commonly called the twelve-spotted skimmer.
This dragonfly has a brownish-black body with yellow spots on its abdomen and wings.
It has a wingspan of about 2.5 to 3 inches and a slender body that is approximately 2.5 inches in length.
The wings are clear with brown spots and the thorax is adorned with white stripes.
These dragonflies can be found near freshwater habitats such as lakes, ponds, and marshes.
They are active during the day and are known for their fast and agile flight.
The Libellula pulchella is an important predator in aquatic ecosystems, feeding on insects and other small invertebrates.
